<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1877,2015]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,369,1914,1940]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribution:</emphasis>
worldwide in tropical and subtropical regions. The species has been introduced into 
<collectingCountry box="[151,244,1952,1978]" name="Mexico" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, where its presence was first reported in 
<number box="[721,780,1952,1978]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="1940.0">1940</number>
by Taylor and then by 
<bibRefCitation author="Burt" box="[1051,1324,1952,1978]" pageId="11" pageNumber="26" refString="Burt, C. E. &amp; Myers, G. S. (1942) Neotropical lizards in the collection of the Natural History Museum of Stanford University. Stanford University Publications, University Series, Biological Sciences, 8, 273 - 324." type="journal article" year="1942">
Burt and Myers (
<number box="[1251,1315,1952,1978]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="1942.0">1942</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,341,1989,2015]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Subspecies:</emphasis>
Not described. However the species is chromosomally polytypic (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,700]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,339,151,177]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Karyotype:</emphasis>
the chromosomal complement of this species is variable with 
<number box="[1074,1088,152,178]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2.0">2</number>
n = 
<number box="[1136,1165,152,178]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="40.0">40</number>
and 
<number box="[1223,1237,152,178]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2.0">2</number>
n = 
<number box="[1284,1317,152,178]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="46.0">46</number>
. However the karyotype with 
<number box="[382,396,189,215]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2.0">2</number>
n = 
<number box="[445,474,189,215]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="46.0">46</number>
clearly belongs to 
<taxonomicName box="[702,854,189,214]" class="Reptilia" family="Gekkonidae" genus="Hemidactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bowringii">
<emphasis box="[702,854,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">H. bowringii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Kupriyanova" box="[918,1310,189,215]" pageId="12" pageNumber="28" refString="Kupriyanova, L. A. &amp; Darevski, I. S. (1989). Karyotypic Uniformity in east Asian populations of Hemidactylus frenatus. Journal of Herpetology, 23, 294 - 296." type="journal article" year="1989">
Kupriyanova and Darevski 
<number box="[1246,1310,189,215]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Sporadic presence of triploid populations with 
<number box="[629,643,226,252]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="3.0">3</number>
n = 
<number box="[695,726,226,252]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="60.0">60</number>
has been found in 
<collectingCountry box="[970,1076,226,252]" name="Vietnam" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Darevsky" box="[1093,1366,226,252]" pageId="12" pageNumber="26" refString="Darevsky, I. S., Kupriyanova, L. A. &amp; Roshchin, V. V. (1984) A new all-female triploid species of gecko and karyological data on the bisexual Hemidactylus frenatus from Vietnam. Journal of Herpetology, 18, 277 - 284." type="book chapter" year="1984">
Darevsky 
<emphasis box="[1224,1289,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1298,1366,226,252]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The specimens from Chamela conform to the most common karyotype with 
<number box="[1019,1033,264,290]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2.0">2</number>
n = 
<number box="[1082,1112,264,290]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="40.0">40</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[1129,1203,264,290]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[151,254,1698,1722]" captionTargetBox="[227,1334,864,1642]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[188,1398,826,1677]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5. Karyotype of Hemidactylus frenatus, female (2 n = 40 and FN = 54)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196011/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Fig. 
<number box="[1186,1203,264,290]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). This karyotype is composed of seven pairs of biarmed chromosomes (three large pairs and four pairs of small chromomomes). The remaining chromosomes are telocentrics. This is the first description of the karyotype of this species in the New World.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,700]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,400,413,439]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[196,259,413,439]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">DNA</collectionCode>
taxonomy:
</emphasis>
the rDNA 
<number box="[533,563,413,439]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="16.0">16</number>
S has been studied in specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1013,1154,413,439]" name="Madagascar" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation box="[1200,1436,413,439]" pageId="12" pageNumber="29" refString="Vences, M., Wanke, S., Vieites, D. R., Branch, W. R., Glaw, F. &amp; Meyer, A. (2004) Natural colonization or introduction? Phylogeographical relationships and morphological differentiation of house geckos (Hemidactylus) from Madagascar. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, 83, 115 - 130." type="journal article">
Vences 
<emphasis box="[1291,1350,413,438]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[1366,1428,413,439]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2004.0">2004</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and in one single specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[545,774,450,476]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Whiting" box="[790,1028,450,476]" pageId="12" pageNumber="29" refString="Whiting, A. S., Bauer, A. M. &amp; Sites Jr., J. W. (2003) Phylogenetic relationships and limb loss in sub-Saharan African scincine lizards (Squamata: Scincidae), Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 29, 582 - 598." type="journal article" year="2003">
Whiting 
<emphasis box="[896,956,450,475]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[964,1028,450,476]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The sequence comparison shows that the specimen studied here is almost identical to the one from Oceania (sequence divergence: 0.2%) but differs more from those of 
<collectingCountry box="[466,608,525,551]" name="Madagascar" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
(sequence divergence: 0.8–3.1%). Oceania is believed to represent the centre of origin of the species from which it spreads worldwide due to human movements. The close relationships among the two haplotypes agree with a recent arrival of the species in 
<collectingCountry box="[1199,1297,600,626]" name="Mexico" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. In fact, 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Gekkonidae" genus="Hemidactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="frenatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">H. frenatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was probably introduced during the Spaniard dominium of 
<collectingCountry box="[962,1056,637,663]" name="Mexico" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. The importation likely dates to the time when Spanish galleons carried trade goods between Acapulco and the 
<collectingCountry box="[1078,1210,674,700]" name="Philippines" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Philippines</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Taylor" box="[1225,1373,674,700]" pageId="12" pageNumber="29" refString="Taylor, E. H. (1940) Mexican snakes of the genus Typhlops. University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 26, 441 - 444." type="journal article" year="1940">
Taylor 
<number box="[1310,1373,674,700]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1940.0">1940</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
